Exercise 6.5.4 - Decision Tree Modeling - Mortality Data

W. Mangrobang

September 07, 2018

Problem Statement

Build a regression model using at least three predictor variables. Consider using the AutoClaim or diamonds datasets, but any data you have will do. The purpose of this exercise is to perform various tests of the assumptions for ordinary least squares regression. When finished, report on the forum your dataset choice, your target and predictor variables, and which of the assumptions appear to have been met. CHUNK 12 has some code snippets that may help.

+ The mean of the residuals is zero (note that in most cases this is an assured outcome of the parameter estimation process).

+ The variance is constant (homoscedasticity). Residual plots are commonly used. R makes four useful plots.

  • The residuals have no autocorrelation. We have not had a time series component to our data. With no preset order to the observations, it makes no sense to check this assumption.

+ The residuals and the predictor variables are uncorrelated. A hypothesis test that the correlation is zero can be done.

+ The residuals have a normal distribution. This can be checked via a q- q plot or a histogram.

  • I selected the diamonds dataset.
  • Target variable: price
  • Predictor variables: depth, table, caret

# run the regression
model <- lm(price ~ depth + table + carat, data = diamonds)

+ The mean of the residuals is zero (note that in most cases this is an assured outcome of the parameter estimation process).

# Check the mean of the residuals
mean(model$residuals)
## [1] -1.938156e-12

Basically zero.

+ The variance is constant (homoscedasticity). Residual plots are commonly used. R makes four useful plots.

+ Check that the residuals have a normal distribution

# Check the residuals for constant variance. Not all four plots relate to
# this assumption.
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(model)

Homoscedasticity - Fails. Note the Scale-Location plot and how there appears to be a distintive shape/pattern to the scatter. With constant variance we expect to see an even, shapeless distribution across the plot.

Normality - Fails. For the QQ-Plot, we expect to see points to align along the 45 degree line across all quantiles. This is the case in the middle quantiles, but the ends diverge significantly.

…Another option is to make a histogram of the residuals.

resid <- data.frame(model$residuals)
ggplot(resid, aes(x = model.residuals)) + geom_histogram(position = "identity", 
    col = "black")

It seems roughly ‘bell-shaped’ but qq-plot tells a clearer story of normality failure at the tails.

Check that the residuals and the predictor variables are uncorrelated

cor.test(diamonds$depth, model$residuals, method = "pearson")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  diamonds$depth and model$residuals
## t = 1.6268e-13, df = 53938, p-value = 1

## t = -3.632e-13, df = 53938, p-value = 1

## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.008439066  0.008439066
## sample estimates:
##           cor 
## -1.563883e-15

Appears that residuals are uncorrelated with all three target variables.
+ High p-values suggest not rejecting the null hypothesis that the correlation is 0.
+ The 95% confidence intervals are centered around 0.
